n to present Indigenous critiques and assessments of this phenomenon. The volume connects two disciplines and strands of scholarship: German Studies and Indigenous Studies, focusing on how Indianthusiam has created both barriers and opportunities for Indigenous peoples with Germans and in Germany.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCross-cultural studieszGermany. 0aCross-cultural studieszNorth America. 0aIndigenous peopleszNorth AmericaxAttitudes. 0aIndigenous peopleszNorth AmericaxPublic opinion. 0aIntercultural communicationzGermany. 0aIntercultural communicationzNorth America. 4aGerman Studies. 4aIndigenous Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Indigenous Studies.2bisacsh  a.  aGerman colonial history.  aGerman powwows.  aIndianertuemlei.  aIndianthusiam.  aIndigenous Studies at German Universities.  aKarl May.  aNative ambassadors in Europe.  acultural appropriation.  ahobbyism.  aidentity.  aindigeneity.  aracism.  arepresentation.  atranscultural connections and relationships.  atransnational contact zones.1 aLutz, Hartmut, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aStrzelczyk, Florentine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWatchman, Renae, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311127268908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2019z978311127498040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978177112401040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781771124010423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781771124010/original  a978-3-11-127268-9  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  a978-3-11-127498-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles